          "title": "The bed too short and the strange work of God (28:20-22)",
          "body": "Verse 20 may be the chapter's most arresting domestic image: 'the bed is too short on which to stretch out, and the blanket is too small to wrap oneself in.' The wisdom-saying captures the radical insufficiency of the false covenant — the diplomatic arrangement Jerusalem has constructed simply does not cover what it promises to cover. You cannot stretch out in it; you cannot get warm in it. The statement is not an argument; it is a picture that arrests the imagination at a level below argument. Then v. 21 names what is happening with theological precision: God is performing His 'unusual task,' His 'extraordinary work.' The terms zur (foreign, strange) and nokhri (alien) are used — what God is doing in bringing judgment upon His own covenant people is alien to His normal character of rescue and redemption. This is significant pastoral theology: Isaiah does not pretend that God's judgment on Israel is comfortable or routine for God. It is strange. It is not what He is known for in the covenant relationship. The precedents of Perazim and Gibeon are invoked not to celebrate this judgment but to establish that the same power that once fought for Israel is now engaged against her — and that weight is supposed to break through the scoffers' insouciance. Verse 22 closes with the last pastoral appeal: 'do not carry on as scoffers, or your fetters will be made stronger.' The decree of destruction is heard (v. 22b), but the appeal is still extended. Isaiah never issues doom without also issuing the invitation to stop."
