          "title": "The farmer parable — graduated wisdom, not wanton destruction (28:23-29)",
          "body": "The chapter closes with a wisdom poem that is the interpretive key to everything preceding it. Isaiah asks the audience to observe a farmer at work. The farmer does not plow endlessly — he plows in order to plant (v. 24). He does not sow with reckless uniformity — he plants each crop in its proper location with the proper method (v. 25). He does not thresh with one instrument regardless of crop — dill gets the rod, cumin gets the club, grain gets the wheel, but none gets more than it can bear (vv. 27-28). And the source of this differentiated, purposive wisdom? 'His God instructs and teaches him properly' (v. 26). The parable does not merely illustrate divine governance — it attributes agricultural wisdom itself to divine instruction. God is behind the farmer's graduated expertise. The conclusion in v. 29 completes the transfer: 'This also comes from the LORD of hosts, who has made His counsel wonderful and His wisdom great.' The 'this also' is a profound logical move. The parables of judgment in the preceding verses — the storm, the trampling, the cancelled covenant, the strange work — all of this participates in the same wonderful counsel and great wisdom that governs the farmer's careful differentiation between crops. God has not used a threshing sledge on cummin. He has not threshed grain forever. He knows what He is doing, He knows how long to do it, and He knows when to stop."
